description:
Make hxrt understandable as a deliberately selective semantic runtime rather than an opaque support library. Documentation must help contributors decide whether code belongs in direct generated C, a program-local specialization, or a named hxrt slice, and must help users inspect why a build selected runtime code and how to remove it when possible.

Scope:
- document the design decision for hxrt and the compiler-first/direct-C hierarchy;
- explain the complete TypedExpr to HxcIR runtime-intent to feature-root/dependency-closure to runtime-plan/project-emission flow;
- document runtime policies, provenance, empty-plan/no-runtime behavior, ABI/versioning, ownership, failure, allocation, threading, and platform boundaries;
- give every production hxrt header/source a clear file-level purpose, selection trigger, callers/consumers, dependencies, and lifecycle contract, plus inline comments for non-obvious invariants and algorithms;
- maintain a reviewable per-feature catalog covering semantic reason, roots, dependencies, files, symbols, alternatives considered, and why direct or program-local C is insufficient;
- connect the prose to machine-owned feature/manifest facts so source, registry, plans, tests, and documentation cannot silently drift;
- document inspection and minimization workflows with runtime-free and minimum-runtime examples.

Fixture-only native code remains labeled as such and cannot be described as selected generated-program runtime support.

Caxecraft needs modular world, ray, and collision functions over one fixed CArray-backed voxel buffer. The existing bounded storage slice proves only lexical local Span and ConstSpan borrows; neither type can cross a function boundary. Without a reusable compiler capability, the game would need one monolithic function, a general Array runtime, raw pointers, or a game-specific compiler path.

Scope:
- admit c.Span<T> and c.ConstSpan<T> parameters on reached direct static Haxe functions;
- accept arguments borrowed from an admitted local CArray or forwarded from another admitted span parameter;
- retain IRTSpan in HxcIR and lower the internal C signature to an element pointer plus size_t length;
- create a callee-local non-escaping borrow so ordinary checked indexing keeps its exact forwarded length;
- preserve mutable versus const pointee qualifiers, evaluation order, deterministic naming, and source spans;
- keep return, field, global, native/export ABI, callback, closure, virtual, recursive, and escaping span forms fail-closed.

Non-scope: general pointers, slicing, owned buffers, dynamic arrays, public ABI stabilization, arbitrary iterator escape, or Caxecraft-named compiler logic.

CArray can own and mutate exact-width UInt8 storage, but generated Haxe still needs a typed way to construct and inspect those values. Haxe cast is an unchecked type assertion and is deliberately forbidden by the repository typed-boundary policy. ADR 0008 already defines exact and modulo conversion semantics, so this task exposes the safe direct subset through c.IntConvert.

Scope:
- add typed c.IntConvert.exact and c.IntConvert.modulo operations with result-context target inference;
- require full source-range containment for exact and an unsigned target for modulo;
- admit only existing primitive decisions that are non-failing and IRIStatic;
- retain exact/wrapping HxcIR meaning and structural C casts;
- cover literal and dynamic Int-to-UInt8 plus UInt8-to-Int and the coherent exact-width family;
- preserve evaluation order, deterministic dumps, no-runtime proof, source positions, and strict C11 safety.

Non-scope: unchecked Haxe cast admission, implicit lossy assignments, checked or failing conversions, signed-target reconstruction helpers, arithmetic directly on exact-width carriers, ABI-width integers, enum-abstract lowering, or a Caxecraft-specific compiler path.

Assemble the first honest playable example through the production C target and the admitted RaylibHx surface.

The initial game is a deliberately finite voxel sandbox:
- open a raylib window and run a conventional update/draw loop;
- render deterministic colored terrain with no external asset pipeline;
- first-person mouse look, WASD movement, gravity, jump, collision, and cursor capture;
- DDA crosshair picking with left-click removal and right-click placement;
- a crosshair, concise controls/status HUD, frame/update counters, and an obvious quit path;
- render only exposed blocks in the baseline path and retain simple counters for world cells, visible blocks, and draw calls;
- use a fixed-step domain update with interpolated or ordinary rendering as the accepted design decides.

All application source must be ordinary Haxe plus the typed raylib companion and reusable c.* contracts. Generated C and build artifacts remain owned by the normal compiler pipeline. If the implementation adapts an upstream raylib example, preserve the required zlib attribution and record exactly what was adapted; an independent implementation is preferred.

Non-scope: textures, resource-owning meshes, audio, procedural infinite worlds, crafting, enemies, save/load, multiplayer, a custom engine abstraction, or claiming optimized rendering.

Implement the raylib-independent game domain before the interactive shell so the hardest gameplay logic is deterministic, portable in shape, and directly testable.

Scope:
- a compact BlockKind representation and a finite world of at least 32 x 16 x 32 cells;
- typed block/world coordinates, checked bounds, overflow-safe 3D-to-linear indexing, and deterministic seeded terrain generation;
- block query, replace, remove, and place rules;
- Amanatides-Woo style voxel DDA returning hit cell, previous empty cell, hit face/normal, distance, and explicit miss;
- a first-person player state with velocity, gravity, jump/grounded state, and axis-resolved AABB collision against solid blocks;
- fixed-step domain update inputs so test traces do not depend on wall-clock or renderer timing;
- a narrow storage adapter over the reusable fixed CArray capability.

Keep raylib types, input polling, drawing, window state, and platform facts out of these modules. Use ordinary Haxe domain types and algorithms wherever possible. This is the seam a later portability experiment may reuse, but C correctness and bounded performance are the current authority.

Non-scope: infinite terrain, chunk streaming, save files, networking, mobs, crafting, lighting, textures, or Rust/JavaScript target adapters.

Create a deterministic consumer/provisioning lane for the exact raylib version without making the compiler or package depend on ../raylib or a network fetch during ordinary compilation.

Required lanes:
- checksum-pinned source provisioning used by CI and the canonical example;
- an explicit user-supplied/offline source or installed-library path;
- an optional system pkg-config lane whose resolved version/flags are recorded rather than assumed;
- direct argument-array consumption plus the neutral build manifest;
- native desktop builds for Linux, macOS, and Windows, with exact platform libraries/frameworks;
- a raylib 6.0 PLATFORM_MEMORY/software-renderer or other reviewed headless lane for deterministic CI where feasible.

Normal generated artifacts remain Reflaxe-owned. Provisioning, dependency compilation, and caches remain orchestration inputs with normalized reports and no checkout/temp paths serialized.

Non-scope: claiming every raylib platform, bundling raylib binaries into the Haxe package, implicit latest-version downloads, or turning example setup into compiler semantics.

Build the curated Haxe-facing layer on top of raylib.raw.*. It should remain visually and behaviorally close to raylib while using Haxe where the gain is real.

Candidate ergonomic wins to ratify and implement:
- familiar raylib.Raylib entry points with typed enum abstracts and direct inline forwarding;
- safe literal String-to-CString conversion for window titles and HUD text;
- discoverable Vector2/Vector3/Color/Camera constructors and constants;
- compile-time-checked window/input/camera choices;
- explicit borrowed, owned, nullable, retained, callback, variadic, and unsafe boundaries;
- direct access to raylib.raw.* as the typed escape hatch.

A wrapper must be direct/inlined or report its allocation/runtime/error effects. Do not add one wrapper object per C value. Begin/End scope helpers are deferred unless closure inlining, cleanup on every edge, and zero-allocation behavior are proven; direct calls remain first-class.

Review source familiarity with the existing hxcpp raylib-hx API, but generate this API independently from the accepted architecture and the raylib header.

Non-scope: game-domain helpers, a scene graph, ECS, renderer, asset manager, hidden GC ownership, or broad macros for aesthetic syntax.

Raylib exposes C float pervasively, while ADR 0008 intentionally maps ordinary Haxe Float to binary64 double. Add the reusable exact C scalar needed to represent imported float fields, parameters, returns, arrays, and constants without collapsing the two semantic types.

Scope:
- a typed c.Float32 contract and matching HxcIR/C AST representation;
- target validation for the admitted binary32 C float ABI;
- explicit, semantics-documented Float <-> c.Float32 conversions, including NaN, infinities, signed zero, subnormals, finite rounding, and overflow policy;
- literal construction and imported struct/function use;
- deterministic dumps, malformed/unsupported target diagnostics, native probes, and differential tests.

This work is a focused child of E6.T03 discovered while auditing raylib 6.0. It must remain useful for any C library and must not change Haxe Float away from binary64.

Non-scope: vector math APIs, fast-math, half/extended floats, implicit lossy conversion hidden inside arbitrary assignments, or raylib-specific names.

Extend the reusable E2.T08 fixed-array/span slice so a bounded game world can use compact mutable storage without an enormous source literal or a general Haxe Array runtime.

Scope:
- a typed, compile-time-sized zero-initialized CArray construction form;
- repeated indexed reads/writes and mutable/const span borrowing;
- safe three-dimensional-to-linear indexing implemented in ordinary Haxe;
- deterministic automatic storage for the initial finite world, with explicit size/bounds policy;
- structural HxcIR and CAST lowering with no runtime feature selection.

Any new intrinsic or macro must pass the repository admission policy and remain generally useful. Do not introduce a Caxecraft-named compiler hook.

Non-scope: dynamic resizing, heap ownership, general Haxe Array/Bytes parity, unbounded stack allocation, or static/global megabuffers.

Implement the smallest reusable E6 production slice that lets typed, hand-authored extern declarations call an existing C library without waiting for full bindgen breadth.

Admitted scope:
- exact non-variadic C calling-convention functions;
- C scalars, typedef identity, closed enum/constant values, and by-value imported structs;
- imported struct field read/write, by-value arguments, and by-value returns;
- borrowed literal CString arguments with embedded-NUL rejection and explicit lifetime;
- authoritative header inclusion plus logical library/pkg-config/framework build facts;
- structural TypedExpr -> HxcIR -> CAST lowering, source-positioned diagnostics, deterministic symbols/manifests, and normal Reflaxe output ownership.

This is reusable compiler work contributing to E6.T03-E6.T05 and E6.T09. It must not special-case raylib names or treat the game as ABI evidence.

Non-scope: callbacks, variadics, retained pointers, opaque resource ownership, C++, general bindgen, public C exports, or arbitrary raw C.

Context: Build a high-quality Haxe layer for raylib and a fun end-to-end C game named Caxecraft. The result should prove that ordinary typed Haxe can compile through the production C target, consume a real C framework directly, retain inspectable performance, and improve authoring ergonomics without hiding the underlying API.

Product architecture:
- raylib remains the native runtime, renderer, platform layer, and ABI authority;
- an extraction-ready Haxe companion surface incubates in this repository;
- an ABI-faithful raw layer remains available, while a semantic Haxe layer adds only proven zero-cost or explicitly costed ergonomics;
- Caxecraft is a finite, playable voxel sandbox with procedural terrain, first-person movement, block picking/removal/placement, collision, and a measured rendering path;
- all generated C and build facts flow through normal compiler ownership; no raw __c__, hand-authored generated output, example-specific compiler branch, or sibling-checkout dependency is allowed.

Pinned starting oracle: raylib 6.0 tag at commit dbc56a87da87d973a9c5baa4e7438a9d20121d28. The pin, header hashes, flags, licenses, and ABI probes must be recorded before support is claimed.

Coordination: reusable foreign-call, imported-layout, CString, fixed-storage, and build-plan capabilities belong in compiler/interop issues and must not be implemented as Caxecraft-only shortcuts. The current E3.T06 work remains independently scoped.

Deferred scope: compiling the same game to Rust or JavaScript is a separate follow-up. The first iteration may preserve clean domain/platform seams, but it must optimize for honest C/raylib ergonomics and performance rather than pretend target portability is already proven.

acceptance_criteria:
- cyclic graphs collect correctly;
- exception cleanup tests pass;
- runtime plan includes only reachable features;
- `-D hxc_runtime=none` succeeds for eligible fixtures and gives reasoned errors for ineligible fixtures.

- consumers build independently;
- exceptions and ownership are translated correctly;
- headers compile under C and C++;
- ABI diff gate detects intentional and accidental changes.

- agreed upstream test threshold reached with no silent skips;
- every gap is explicit and tracked;
- portable todo domain compiles on C and selected sibling targets.

- direct calls devirtualize in reports;
- recursive enums and generic containers work;
- nonescaping closures allocate no heap memory;
- C output remains warning-clean.

- clean user journey from install to `hxc new`, `hxc run`;
- JSON output supports automation;
- existing build systems can consume the manifest without generated CMake/Meson.

- no release-blocking correctness, UB, security, or ABI issues;
- all 1.0 gates have archived evidence;
- immutable release artifacts and provenance are published;
- post-1.0 compatibility policy is documented.

- SQLite and zlib-class libraries bind from headers reproducibly;
- regenerated output is clean;
- ABI facts match compiled C probes;
- unsupported constructs produce precise diagnostics.

- examples use no unapproved `__c__`;
- todo generated C is reviewed against a hand-written baseline;
- docs state limitations honestly;
- benchmark results are reproducible.
